    overview: "Glucose is the most commonly measured clinical chemistry analyte. Accurate measurement is critical for diabetes diagnosis and management. Reference method: hexokinase. Common methods: glucose oxidase (POC meters), hexokinase (reference/automated analyzers). Diagnosis: fasting plasma glucose ≥126 mg/dL, random ≥200 with symptoms, 2h OGTT ≥200, or HbA1c ≥6.5%.",
    mechanismPhysiology: "Hexokinase method (reference): Glucose + ATP → G-6-P + ADP (hexokinase). G-6-P + NADP+ → 6-PG + NADPH (G6PD). NADPH measured at 340 nm. Highly specific for glucose. Glucose oxidase (GOD) method: Glucose + O2 → gluconic acid + H2O2 (glucose oxidase). H2O2 + chromogen → color (peroxidase). Ascorbic acid (vitamin C) and other reducing substances interfere by consuming H2O2 (false negatives). Electrochemical glucose meters (POC): glucose oxidase or glucose dehydrogenase on test strip. Measure current proportional to glucose concentration.",
    clinicalRelevance: "Diabetes diagnostic criteria (ADA): FPG ≥126 mg/dL (fasting ≥8 hours), random PG ≥200 + symptoms, 2h OGTT ≥200 (75g glucose load), HbA1c ≥6.5%. Prediabetes: FPG 100-125 (impaired fasting glucose), 2h OGTT 140-199 (impaired glucose tolerance), HbA1c 5.7-6.4%. Gestational DM screening: 50g GCT at 24-28 weeks → if ≥130-140 mg/dL at 1h → 100g 3-hour OGTT.",
