    complications: "Glycolysis in unfluoridated specimens: 5-7% decrease per hour at room temperature. POC meters with GDH-PQQ enzyme: cross-react with maltose, galactose, xylose (falsely elevated)—dangerous in peritoneal dialysis patients receiving icodextrin. Hemolyzed specimens: variable interference depending on method.",
    clinicalPearls: ["Fluoride/oxalate (gray top) INHIBITS glycolysis—essential to prevent falsely low glucose if processing is delayed", "Plasma glucose is 10-15% HIGHER than whole blood glucose—POC meters often report plasma-equivalent values", "POC glucose meters should NOT be used for diabetes DIAGNOSIS—only for monitoring"],
    examPitfalls: ["Without fluoride, glucose decreases 5-7% per HOUR at room temperature due to RBC glycolysis", "GDH-PQQ glucose meters cross-react with maltose (from icodextrin dialysis)—can cause dangerously falsely high readings", "Hexokinase is the REFERENCE method—more specific than glucose oxidase which can be affected by reducing substances"],
    faqJson: [{ question: "Why is the gray-top tube important?", answer: "The gray-top tube contains fluoride (glycolytic inhibitor) and oxalate (anticoagulant). Fluoride inhibits enolase in the glycolytic pathway, preventing cells from consuming glucose. Without it, glucose decreases 5-7% per hour as RBCs and WBCs metabolize glucose." }, { question: "Why can't POC meters be used for diagnosis?", answer: "POC glucose meters have wider acceptable error ranges (±15-20%) than laboratory analyzers. This variability can cause misclassification near diagnostic cutpoints (e.g., a true glucose of 120 could read as 138 or 102 on a POC meter). ADA recommends laboratory-grade methods for diagnosis." }]
